# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: delta-lake
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:delta-lake/acid] In computer science, **ACID** (atomicity, consistency, isolation, durability) is a set of properties of database transactions intended to guarantee data validity despite errors, power failures, and other mishaps.
[src:delta-lake/acid] For example, a transfer of funds from one bank account to another, involving multiple changes such as debiting one account and crediting another, is a single transaction.
[src:delta-lake/acid] In 1983, Andreas Reuter and Theo Härder coined the acronym *ACID*, building on earlier work by Jim Gray who named atomicity, consistency, and durability, but not isolation, when characterizing the transaction concept.
[src:delta-lake/acid] These four properties are the major guarantees of the transaction paradigm, which has influenced many aspects of development in database systems.
[src:delta-lake/acid] According to Gray and Reuter, the IBM Information Management System supported ACID transactions as early as 1973 (although the acronym was created later).
[src:delta-lake/acid] BASE stands for **b**asically **a**vailable, **s**oft state, and **e**ventually consistent: the acronym highlights that BASE is opposite of ACID, like their chemical equivalents, acid and base.
[src:delta-lake/acid] A database either leans towards ACID or BASE, but it cannot be both (according to CAP theorem).
[src:delta-lake/acid] For example, SQL databases (like MySQL, PostgreSQL, AWS RedShift) are structured over the ACID model, while NoSQL databases (like DynamoDB or MongoDB) use the BASE architecture.
[src:delta-lake/acid] However, some NoSQL databases might exhibit certain ACID traits.
[src:delta-lake/acid] Transactions are often composed of multiple statements.
[src:delta-lake/acid] Atomicity guarantees that each transaction is treated as a single "unit", which either succeeds completely or fails completely: if any of the statements constituting a transaction fails to complete, the entire transaction fails and the database is left unchanged.
[src:delta-lake/acid] An atomic system must guarantee atomicity in each and every situation, including power failures, errors, and crashes.
[src:delta-lake/acid] A guarantee of atomicity prevents updates to the database from occurring only partially, which can cause greater problems than rejecting the whole series outright.
[src:delta-lake/acid] As a consequence, the transaction cannot be observed to be in progress by another database client.
[src:delta-lake/acid] At one moment in time, it has not yet happened, and at the next, it has already occurred in whole (or nothing happened if the transaction was cancelled in progress).
[src:delta-lake/acid] Consistency ensures that a transaction can only bring the database from one consistent state to another, preserving database invariants: any data written to the database must be valid according to all defined rules, including constraints, cascades, triggers, and any combination thereof.
[src:delta-lake/acid] This prevents database corruption by an illegal transaction.
[src:delta-lake/acid] An example of a database invariant is referential integrity, which guarantees the primary key–foreign key relationship.
[src:delta-lake/acid] Transactions are often executed concurrently (e.g., multiple transactions reading and writing to a table at the same time).
[src:delta-lake/acid] Isolation ensures that concurrent execution of transactions leaves the database in the same state that would have been obtained if the transactions were executed sequentially.
[src:delta-lake/acid] Isolation is the main goal of concurrency control; depending on the isolation level used, the effects of an incomplete transaction might not be visible to other transactions.
[src:delta-lake/acid] Durability guarantees that once a transaction has been committed, it will remain committed even in the case of a system failure (e.g., power outage or crash).
[src:delta-lake/acid] This usually means that completed transactions (or their effects) are recorded in non-volatile memory.
[src:delta-lake/acid] The following examples further illustrate the ACID properties.
[src:delta-lake/acid] In these examples, the database table has two columns, A and B.
[src:delta-lake/acid] An integrity constraint requires that the value in A and the value in B must sum to 100.
[src:delta-lake/acid] Atomicity is the guarantee that series of database operations in an atomic transaction will either all occur (a successful operation), or none will occur (an unsuccessful operation).
[src:delta-lake/acid] The series of operations cannot be separated with only some of them being executed, which makes the series of operations "indivisible".
[src:delta-lake/acid] In other words, atomicity means indivisibility and irreducibility.
[src:delta-lake/acid] Alternatively, we may say that a logical transaction may be composed of several physical transactions.
[src:delta-lake/acid] Unless and until all component physical transactions are executed, the logical transaction will not have occurred.
[src:delta-lake/acid] An example of an atomic transaction is a monetary transfer from bank account A to account B.
[src:delta-lake/acid] It consists of two operations, withdrawing the money from account A and depositing it to account B.
[src:delta-lake/acid] We would not want to see the amount removed from account A before we are sure it has also been transferred into account B.
[src:delta-lake/acid] Performing these operations in an atomic transaction ensures that the database remains in a consistent state, that is, money is neither debited nor credited if either of those two operations fails.
[src:delta-lake/acid] Consistency is a very general term, which demands that the data must meet all validation rules.
[src:delta-lake/acid] In the previous example, the validation is a requirement that *A* + *B* = 100.
[src:delta-lake/acid] All validation rules must be checked to ensure consistency.
[src:delta-lake/acid] Assume that a transaction attempts to subtract 10 from *A* without altering *B*.
[src:delta-lake/acid] Because consistency is checked after each transaction, it is known that *A* + *B* = 100 before the transaction begins.
[src:delta-lake/acid] If the transaction removes 10 from *A* successfully, atomicity will be achieved.
[src:delta-lake/acid] However, a validation check will show that *A* + *B* = 90, which is inconsistent with the rules of the database.
[src:delta-lake/acid] The entire transaction must be canceled and the affected rows rolled back to their pre-transaction state.
[src:delta-lake/acid] If there had been other constraints, triggers, or cascades, every single change operation would have been checked in the same way as above before the transaction was committed.
[src:delta-lake/acid] Similar issues may arise with other constraints.
[src:delta-lake/acid] We may have required the data types of both *A* and *B* to be integers.
[src:delta-lake/acid] If we were then to enter, say, the value 13.5 for *A*, the transaction will be canceled, or the system may give rise to an alert in the form of a trigger (if/when the trigger has been written to this effect).
[src:delta-lake/acid] Another example would be integrity constraints, which would not allow us to delete a row in one table whose primary key is referred to by at least one foreign key in other tables.
[src:delta-lake/acid] To demonstrate isolation, we assume two transactions execute at the same time, each attempting to modify the same data.
[src:delta-lake/acid] One of the two must wait until the other completes in order to maintain isolation.
[src:delta-lake/acid] If these operations are performed in order, isolation is maintained, although T2 must wait.
[src:delta-lake/acid] Consider what happens if T1 fails halfway through.
[src:delta-lake/acid] The database eliminates T1's effects, and T2 sees only valid data.
[src:delta-lake/acid] Again, consider what happens if T1 fails while modifying B in Step 4.
[src:delta-lake/acid] By the time T1 fails, T2 has already modified A; it cannot be restored to the value it had before T1 without leaving an invalid database.
[src:delta-lake/acid] This is known as a write-write contention, because two transactions attempted to write to the same data field.
[src:delta-lake/acid] In a typical system, the problem would be resolved by reverting to the last known good state, canceling the failed transaction T1, and restarting the interrupted transaction T2 from the good state.
[src:delta-lake/acid] Consider a transaction that transfers 10 from A to B.
[src:delta-lake/acid] First, it removes 10 from A, then it adds 10 to B.
[src:delta-lake/acid] At this point, the user is told the transaction was a success.
[src:delta-lake/acid] However, the changes are still queued in the disk buffer waiting to be committed to disk.
[src:delta-lake/acid] Power fails and the changes are lost, but the user assumes (understandably) that the changes persist.
[src:delta-lake/acid] Processing a transaction often requires a sequence of operations that is subject to failure for a number of reasons.
[src:delta-lake/acid] For instance, the system may have no room left on its disk drives, or it may have used up its allocated CPU time.
[src:delta-lake/acid] There are two popular families of techniques: write-ahead logging and shadow paging.
[src:delta-lake/acid] In both cases, locks must be acquired on all information to be updated, and depending on the level of isolation, possibly on all data that may be read as well.
[src:delta-lake/acid] In write ahead logging, durability is guaranteed by writing the prospective change to a persistent log before changing the database.
[src:delta-lake/acid] That allows the database to return to a consistent state in the event of a crash.
[src:delta-lake/acid] In shadowing, updates are applied to a partial copy of the database, and the new copy is activated when the transaction commits.
[src:delta-lake/acid] Many databases rely upon locking to provide ACID capabilities.
[src:delta-lake/acid] Locking means that the transaction marks the data that it accesses so that the DBMS knows not to allow other transactions to modify it until the first transaction succeeds or fails.
[src:delta-lake/acid] The lock must always be acquired before processing data, including data that is read but not modified.
[src:delta-lake/acid] Non-trivial transactions typically require a large number of locks, resulting in substantial overhead as well as blocking other transactions.
[src:delta-lake/acid] For example, if user A is running a transaction that has to read a row of data that user B wants to modify, user B must wait until user A's transaction completes.
[src:delta-lake/acid] Two-phase locking is often applied to guarantee full isolation.
[src:delta-lake/acid] An alternative to locking is multiversion concurrency control, in which the database provides each reading transaction the prior, unmodified version of data that is being modified by another active transaction.
[src:delta-lake/acid] This allows readers to operate without acquiring locks, i.e., writing transactions do not block reading transactions, and readers do not block writers.
[src:delta-lake/acid] Going back to the example, when user A's transaction requests data that user B is modifying, the database provides A with the version of that data that existed when user B started his transaction.
[src:delta-lake/acid] User A gets a consistent view of the database even if other users are changing data.
[src:delta-lake/acid] One implementation, namely snapshot isolation, relaxes the isolation property.
[src:delta-lake/acid] Guaranteeing ACID properties in a distributed transaction across a distributed database, where no single node is responsible for all data affecting a transaction, presents additional complications.
[src:delta-lake/acid] Network connections might fail, or one node might successfully complete its part of the transaction and then be required to roll back its changes because of a failure on another node.
[src:delta-lake/acid] The two-phase commit protocol (not to be confused with two-phase locking) provides atomicity for distributed transactions to ensure that each participant in the transaction agrees on whether the transaction should be committed or not.
[src:delta-lake/acid] Briefly, in the first phase, one node (the coordinator) interrogates the other nodes (the participants), and only when all reply that they are prepared does the coordinator, in the second phase, formalize the transaction.
[src:delta-lake/data-lake] A **data lake** is a system or repository of data stored in its natural, raw format, usually object blobs or files.
[src:delta-lake/data-lake] A data lake is usually a single store of data including raw copies of source system data, sensor data, social data etc., and transformed data used for tasks such as reporting, visualization, advanced analytics, and machine learning.
[src:delta-lake/data-lake] A data lake can include structured data from relational databases (rows and columns), semi-structured data (CSV, logs, XML, JSON), unstructured data (emails, documents, PDFs), and binary data (images, audio, video).
[src:delta-lake/data-lake] A data lake can be established *on premises* (within an organization's data centers) or *in the cloud* (using cloud services).
[src:delta-lake/data-lake] James Dixon, then chief technology officer at Pentaho, coined the term by 2011 to contrast it with data mart, which is a smaller repository of interesting attributes derived from raw data.
[src:delta-lake/data-lake] In promoting data lakes, he argued that data marts have several inherent problems, such as information siloing.
[src:delta-lake/data-lake] PricewaterhouseCoopers (PwC) said that data lakes could "put an end to data silos".
[src:delta-lake/data-lake] Many companies use cloud storage services such as Google Cloud Storage and Amazon S3 or a distributed file system such as Apache Hadoop distributed file system (HDFS).
[src:delta-lake/data-lake] There is a gradual academic interest in the concept of data lakes.
[src:delta-lake/data-lake] For example, Personal DataLake at Cardiff University is a new type of data lake which aims at managing big data of individual users by providing a single point of collecting, organizing, and sharing personal data.
[src:delta-lake/data-lake] Early data lakes, such as Hadoop 1.0, had limited capabilities because it only supported batch-oriented processing (Map Reduce).
[src:delta-lake/data-lake] Interacting with it required expertise in Java, map reduce and higher-level tools like Apache Pig, Apache Spark and Apache Hive (which were also originally batch-oriented).
[src:delta-lake/data-lake] Poorly managed data lakes have been facetiously called data swamps.
[src:delta-lake/data-lake] In June 2015, David Needle characterized "so-called data lakes" as "one of the more controversial ways to manage big data".
[src:delta-lake/data-lake] PwC was also careful to note in their research that not all data lake initiatives are successful.
[src:delta-lake/data-lake] They describe companies that build successful data lakes as gradually maturing their lake as they figure out which data and metadata are important to the organization.
[src:delta-lake/data-lake] Another criticism is that the term *data lake* is used with many different meanings.
[src:delta-lake/data-lake] It may be used to refer to, for example: any tools or data management practices that are not data warehouses; a particular technology for implementation; a raw data reservoir; a hub for ETL offload; or a central hub for self-service analytics.
[src:delta-lake/data-lake] While critiques of data lakes are warranted, in many cases they apply to other data projects as well.
[src:delta-lake/data-lake] For example, the definition of *data warehouse* is also changeable, and not all data warehouse efforts have been successful.
[src:delta-lake/data-lake] In response to various critiques, McKinsey noted that the data lake should be viewed as a service model for delivering business value within the enterprise, not a technology outcome.
[src:delta-lake/delta-io] Delta Lake is an open-source storage framework that enables building a format agnostic Lakehouse architecture with compute engines including Spark, PrestoDB, Flink, Trino, Hive, Snowflake, Google BigQuery, Athena, Redshift, Databricks, Azure Fabric and APIs for Scala, Java, Rust, and Python.
[src:delta-lake/delta-io] With Delta Universal Format aka UniForm, you can read now Delta tables with Iceberg and Hudi clients.
[src:delta-lake/delta-io] Building modern data lakehouse architectures with Delta Lake with forewords by Michael Armbrust and Dominique Brezinski.
[src:delta-lake/delta-io] These whitepapers dive into the features of Lakehouse storage systems and compare Delta Lake, Apache Hudi, and Apache Iceberg.
[src:delta-lake/delta-io] They also explain the benefits of Lakehouse storage systems and show key performance benchmarks.
[src:delta-lake/delta-io] Together we have made Delta Lake the most widely used lakehouse format in the world!
[src:delta-lake/delta-io] Delta Lake is supported by more than 190 developers from over 70 organizations across multiple repositories.
[src:delta-lake/delta-io] Chat with fellow Delta Lake users and contributors, ask questions and share tips.
[src:delta-lake/delta-io] Delta Lake is an independent open-source project and not controlled by any single company.
[src:delta-lake/delta-io] To emphasize this we joined the Delta Lake Project in 2019, which is a sub-project of the Linux Foundation Projects.
[src:delta-lake/delta-io] Within the project, we make decisions based on these rules.
[src:delta-lake/snapshot-isolation] Snapshot isolation has been adopted by several major database management systems, such as InterBase, Firebird, Oracle, MySQL, PostgreSQL, SQL Anywhere, MongoDB and Microsoft SQL Server (2005 and later).
[src:delta-lake/snapshot-isolation] The main reason for its adoption is that it allows better performance than serializability, yet still avoids most of the concurrency anomalies that serializability avoids (but not all).
[src:delta-lake/snapshot-isolation] Snapshot isolation has been used to criticize the ANSI SQL-92 standard's definition of isolation levels, as it exhibits none of the "anomalies" that the SQL standard prohibited, yet is not serializable (the anomaly-free isolation level defined by ANSI).
[src:delta-lake/snapshot-isolation] In spite of its distinction from serializability, snapshot isolation is sometimes referred to as *serializable* by Oracle.
[src:delta-lake/snapshot-isolation] A transaction executing under snapshot isolation appears to operate on a personal *snapshot* of the database, taken at the start of the transaction.
[src:delta-lake/snapshot-isolation] When the transaction concludes, it will successfully commit only if the values updated by the transaction have not been changed externally since the snapshot was taken.
[src:delta-lake/snapshot-isolation] Such a write–write conflict will cause the transaction to abort.
[src:delta-lake/snapshot-isolation] In a *write skew* anomaly, two transactions (T1 and T2) concurrently read an overlapping data set (e.g. values V1 and V2), concurrently make disjoint updates (e.g.
[src:delta-lake/snapshot-isolation] T1 updates V1, T2 updates V2), and finally concurrently commit, neither having seen the update performed by the other.
[src:delta-lake/snapshot-isolation] Were the system serializable, such an anomaly would be impossible, as either T1 or T2 would have to occur "first", and be visible to the other.
[src:delta-lake/snapshot-isolation] In contrast, snapshot isolation permits write skew anomalies.
[src:delta-lake/snapshot-isolation] As a concrete example, imagine V1 and V2 are two balances held by a single person, Phil.
[src:delta-lake/snapshot-isolation] The bank will allow either V1 or V2 to run a deficit, provided the total held in both is never negative (i.e.
[src:delta-lake/snapshot-isolation] Phil initiates two transactions concurrently, T1 withdrawing $200 from V1, and T2 withdrawing $200 from V2.
[src:delta-lake/snapshot-isolation] If the database guaranteed serializable transactions, the simplest way of coding T1 is to deduct $200 from V1, and then verify that V1 + V2 ≥ 0 still holds, aborting if not.
[src:delta-lake/snapshot-isolation] T2 similarly deducts $200 from V2 and then verifies V1 + V2 ≥ 0.
[src:delta-lake/snapshot-isolation] Since the transactions must serialize, either T1 happens first, leaving V1 = −$100, V2 = $100, and preventing T2 from succeeding (since V1 + (V2 − $200) is now −$200), or T2 happens first and similarly prevents T1 from committing.
[src:delta-lake/snapshot-isolation] If the database is under snapshot isolation(MVCC), however, T1 and T2 operate on private snapshots of the database: each deducts $200 from an account, and then verifies that the new total is zero, using the other account value that held when the snapshot was taken.
[src:delta-lake/snapshot-isolation] Since neither *update* conflicts, both commit successfully, leaving V1 = V2 = −$100, and V1 + V2 = −$200.
[src:delta-lake/snapshot-isolation] Some systems built using multiversion concurrency control (MVCC) may support (only) snapshot isolation to allow transactions to proceed without worrying about concurrent operations, and more importantly without needing to re-verify all read operations when the transaction finally commits.
[src:delta-lake/snapshot-isolation] This is convenient because MVCC maintains a series of recent history consistent states.
[src:delta-lake/snapshot-isolation] The only information that must be stored during the transaction is a list of updates made, which can be scanned for conflicts fairly easily before being committed.
[src:delta-lake/snapshot-isolation] However, MVCC systems (such as MarkLogic) will use locks to serialize writes together with MVCC to obtain some of the performance gains and still support the stronger "serializability" level of isolation.
[src:delta-lake/snapshot-isolation] Potential inconsistency problems arising from write skew anomalies can be fixed by adding (otherwise unnecessary) updates to the transactions in order to enforce the serializability property.
[src:delta-lake/snapshot-isolation] Add a special conflict table, which both transactions update in order to create a direct write–write conflict.
[src:delta-lake/snapshot-isolation] Have one transaction "update" a read-only location (replacing a value with the same value) in order to create a direct write–write conflict (or use an equivalent promotion, e.g.
[src:delta-lake/snapshot-isolation] In the example above, we can materialize the conflict by adding a new table which makes the hidden constraint explicit, mapping each person to their *total balance*.
[src:delta-lake/snapshot-isolation] Phil would start off with a total balance of $200, and each transaction would attempt to subtract $200 from this, creating a write–write conflict that would prevent the two from succeeding concurrently.
[src:delta-lake/snapshot-isolation] However, this approach violates the normal form.
[src:delta-lake/snapshot-isolation] Alternatively, we can promote one of the transaction's reads to a write.
[src:delta-lake/snapshot-isolation] For instance, T2 could set V1 = V1, creating an artificial write–write conflict with T1 and, again, preventing the two from succeeding concurrently.
[src:delta-lake/snapshot-isolation] This solution may not always be possible.
[src:delta-lake/snapshot-isolation] In general, therefore, snapshot isolation puts some of the problem of maintaining non-trivial constraints onto the user, who may not appreciate either the potential pitfalls or the possible solutions.
[src:delta-lake/snapshot-isolation] The upside to this transfer is better performance.
[src:delta-lake/snapshot-isolation] Snapshot isolation is called "serializable" mode in Oracle and PostgreSQL versions prior to 9.1, which may cause confusion with the "real serializability" mode.
[src:delta-lake/snapshot-isolation] There are arguments both for and against this decision; what is clear is that users must be aware of the distinction to avoid possible undesired anomalous behavior in their database system logic.
[src:delta-lake/snapshot-isolation] Snapshot isolation arose from work on multiversion concurrency control databases, where multiple versions of the database are maintained concurrently to allow readers to execute without colliding with writers.
[src:delta-lake/snapshot-isolation] Such a system allows a natural definition and implementation of such an isolation level.
[src:delta-lake/snapshot-isolation] InterBase, later owned by Borland, was acknowledged to provide SI rather than full serializability in version 4, and likely permitted write-skew anomalies since its first release in 1985.
[src:delta-lake/snapshot-isolation] Unfortunately, the ANSI SQL-92 standard was written with a lock-based database in mind, and hence is rather vague when applied to MVCC systems.
[src:delta-lake/snapshot-isolation] Berenson *et al.* wrote a paper in 1995 critiquing the SQL standard, and cited snapshot isolation as an example of an isolation level that did not exhibit the standard anomalies described in the ANSI SQL-92 standard, yet still had anomalous behaviour when compared with serializable transactions.
[src:delta-lake/snapshot-isolation] In 2008, Cahill *et al.* showed that write-skew anomalies could be prevented by detecting and aborting "dangerous" triplets of concurrent transactions.
[src:delta-lake/snapshot-isolation] This implementation of serializability is well-suited to multiversion concurrency control databases, and has been adopted in PostgreSQL 9.1, where it is known as Serializable Snapshot Isolation (SSI).
[src:delta-lake/snapshot-isolation] When used consistently, this eliminates the need for the above workarounds.
[src:delta-lake/snapshot-isolation] The downside over snapshot isolation is an increase in aborted transactions.
[src:delta-lake/snapshot-isolation] This can perform better or worse than snapshot isolation with the above workarounds, depending on workload.
